'''''Trimeresurus trigonocephalus''''', commonly known as the '''Sri Lankan green pit viper''', is a moderately [[venomous snake|venomous]] [[pit viper]] [[species]] [[Endemism|endemic]] to [[Sri Lanka]]. No [[subspecies]] are currently recognized.<ref name=ITIS>{{ITIS|id=634936|taxon=''Trimeresurus trigonocephalus'' |accessdate=27 December 2007}}</ref>

==Description==
''T. trigonocephalus'' is a [[Sexual dimorphism|sexually dimorphic]], mid-sized, cylindrical species. These snakes measure {{convert|20|-|25|cm|abbr=on}} at birth, and males grow to a maximum total length of {{convert|60|-|75|cm|abbr=on}}. The neck is distinct from the flattened, triangular head. There is a [[Loreal scales#Herpetology|loreal]] pit on each side of the head. Mid-sized eyes and a short, rounded, broad [[snout]] are present. The males are considerably smaller than females, which can grow up to {{convert|130|cm|abbr=on}} in total length. The ground color of the snake is variable and [[Camouflage|cryptic]]. Typically, it is a green snake with a black [[Variegation|variegated pattern]], and a black [[Temporal scales|temporal]] line is usually present. The wet zone snakes have these black patterns more clearly marked. The [[Vertebral column|vertebral area]] has a tinge of yellow. The tail is black. The [[ventral scales]] are light greenish-yellow or may even be grey. Some snakes have only the black temporal line and the black tail, with the rest of the body being green. In addition, males tend to have a blue coloration, whereas the females are predominantly green. These are bulky snakes with  [[Prehensility|prehensile]], short tails, suiting their [[Arboreal locomotion|arboreal]] lifestyle.<ref name=Malhotra/><ref name=Malhotra2/>

[[File:Sri Lanka Green Pit Viper head detail.jpg|thumb|head details.]]

==Reproduction==
These are [[Vivipary|viviparous]] snakes. About five to 25 young are produced at once.<ref name=Malhotra/><ref name=Malhotra2>{{cite journal |last1=Guo|first1=P.|last2=Jadin|first2=R.C.|last3=Malhotra|first3=Anita|title=An investigation of the cranial evolution of Asian pitvipers (Serpentes: Crotalinae), with comments on the phylogenetic position of Peltopelor macrolepis|year=2009|publisher= Acta Zoologica 91|pages=402<U+2013>407|lastauthoramp=y}}</ref>

==Scales==
''See also: {{See section|Snake scales|Nomenclature of scales}}''

These snakes have two or three large supra[[ocular scales]], and their [[nasal scale]]s are partially divided into two or may not be divided. They have three preoculars, two or three postoculars, 9-10 [[supralabial scale]]s, three or four [[Sublabial scale|infralabials]], and 142-160 [[Ventral scales|ventrals]]; The [[anal scale]] is not divided; their 53-69 [[Subcaudal scales|subcaudals]] are divided. At midbody, the 17-19 rows of [[dorsal scales]] may or may not have [[Keeled scales|keels]]. Most head shields are small and smooth.<ref name=Latreille>{{cite journal |last1=[[Charles-Nicolas-Sigisbert Sonnini de Manoncourt|Sonnini de Manoncourt]]|first1=C.S.|last2=[[Pierre Andr<U+00E9> Latreille|Latreille]]|first2=P.A.|title=Histoire Naturelle des Reptiles, avec Figures Dessinees d'Apres Nature|year=1801|publisher=Paris, Librairie encyclop<U+00E9>dique de Roret|page=332|language=French|lastauthoramp=y}}</ref>

==Common names==
Common names include: Sri Lankan green pit viper,<ref name=Gum04>Gumprecht A, Tillack F, [[:fr:Nikola<U+00EF> Orlov|Orlov NL]], [[Ashok Captain|Captain A]], Ryabov S. 2004. ''Asian Pitvipers''. Geitje Books. Berlin. 1st Edition. 368 pp. ISBN 3-937975-00-4.</ref> Sri Lankan pit viper,<ref name=Meh87>Mehrtens JM. 1987. ''Living Snakes of the World in Color''. New York: Sterling Publishers. 480 pp. ISBN 0-8069-6460-X.</ref> ''pala polonga'' (<U+0DB4><U+0DC5><U+0DCF> <U+0DB4><U+0DDC><U+0DC5><U+0D9F><U+0DCF>), and green pit viper.<ref name=Bro73>{{cite journal|last1=Brown|first1=JH.|title=Toxicology and Pharmacology of Venoms from Poisonous Snakes. Springfield, Illinois|publisher=Charles C. Thomas.|year=1973|lccn=73-229|isbn=0-398-02808-7|page=184}}</ref><ref name=Boulenger1>{{cite journal|last1=[[George Albert Boulenger|Boulenger]]|first1=G.A.|title=Catalogue of the Snakes in the British Museum (Natural History). Volume III., Containing the...Viperid<U+00E6>.|year=1896|publisher=Trustees of the British Museum (Natural History). (Taylor and Francis, Printers.) London|pages=559<U+2013>560}}</ref>

==Geographic range==
It is an endemic species to Sri Lanka and widely distributed in all three [[climatic zone]]s of the island, except higher hills and [[arid]] zones, while relatively more common in wet zone [[grasslands]] and [[rain forest]] areas and occasionally in [[plantations]] of [[cardamom]], [[Cocoa bean|cocoa]], [[coffee]], and [[tea]], from the lower altitudes from {{convert|153|to|1800|m|abbr=on}}.<ref>de Silva, 1980</ref> The [[Type locality (biology)|type locality]] given is "l'<U+00EE>le S.-Eustache" (Sri Lanka).<ref name=McD99/><ref name=silva2>{{cite journal |last1=De Silva|first1=A.|title=Snakes of Sri Lanka: a checklist and an annotated bibliography|year=1998|publisher=Dept. Wildlife Conservation/GEF/UNDP/FAO, Colombo}}</ref><ref name=Suranjan>{{cite journal |last1=Suranjan Karunarathna|first1=D. M. S.|last2=Thasun Amarasinghe|first2=A. A.|title=A Preliminary Survey Of The Reptile Fauna In Nilgala Forest And Its Vicinity, Monaragala District, Sri Lanka|year=2011|publisher=Taprobanica '''03''' (02)|pages=69<U+2013>76|lastauthoramp=y}}</ref>

==Behavior==
It is [[Arboreal locomotion|arboreal]] and [[Nocturnality|nocturnal]], occasionally descending to the ground in search of food such as lizards, frogs, small mammals, and birds. This sluggish [[Crotalinae|pit viper]] is usually encountered on low shrubs during morning hours, but it mostly occupies in grasslands and rain forests. In mornings, it is seen to stay on top of trees to obtain sun rays to heat its body. It uses its tail to hold on to a tree branch. This is not a particularly defensive species, but if agitated, it will vibrate its tail tip, form a sinuous loop with the fore body, and lash and attempt to bite, seldom with a hissing sound. It produces live young mostly during June and July.<ref name=silva>{{cite journal |last1=Das|first1=I.|last2=De Silva|first2=A.|title=Photographic guide to snakes and other reptiles of Sri Lanka|year=2005 |publisher=New Holland Publishers|page=144|lastauthoramp=y}}</ref><ref name=Smith>{{cite journal |last1=[[Malcolm Arthur Smith|Smith]]|first1=M.A.|title=The Fauna of British India, Ceylon and Burma, Including the Whole of the Indo-Chinese Sub-region. Reptilia and Amphibia, Vol. III&mdash;Serpentes|url=http://biodiversitylibrary.org/bibliography/15774|year=1943 |publisher=Secretary of State for India. (Taylor and Francis, Printers.) London|pages=506<U+2013>507}}</ref>

==Venom==
{{see also|Snakebite}}

The venom is primarily [[Haemotoxin|haemotoxic]], with victims experiencing severe pain and swelling of the bitten area, [[oedema]] and [[blister]]s, and localised tissue [[necrosis]]; the pain of the wound may last for a few days. [[Ptosis (eyelid)|Ptosis]] and [[lymphadenopathy]] takes place. Also in some victims, [[Polyuria|polyuric renal failure]] and [[Cardiac electrophysiology|cardiac elecrophysiological]] dysfunction occur, but fatalities have not been reported.<ref name=Malhotra>{{cite journal |last1=Malhotra|first1=Anita|last2=Thorpe|first2=Roger S.|title=A phylogeny of four mitochondrial gene regions suggests a revised taxonomy for Asian pitvipers. (Trimeresurus and Ovophis)|year=2004|publisher=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution '''32'''|pages=83<U+2013>100|lastauthoramp=y}}</ref>

